  <subsection permid="kZg">
    <title>Horizontal Lines and Vertical Lines</title>
    <p permid="Hka">
      We learned in <xref ref="section-standard-form">Section</xref>
      that all lines can be written in <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref>.
      When either <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> equal <m>0</m>,
      we end up with a horizontal or vertical line, as we will soon see.
      Let's take the <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref> line equation,
      let <m>A=0</m> and <m>B=0</m> one at a time and simplify each equation.
    </p>

    <p permid="nrj">
      <md permid="cSe">
        <mrow>Ax+By\amp=C\amp Ax+By\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>\substitute{0}x+By\amp=C\amp Ax+\substitute{0}y\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>By\amp=C\amp Ax\amp=C</mrow>
        <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{C}{B}\amp x\amp=\divideunder{C}{A}</mrow>
        <mrow>y\amp=k\amp x\amp=h</mrow>
      </md>
      At the end we just renamed the constant numbers <m>\frac{C}{B}</m> and
      <m>\frac{C}{A}</m> to <m>k</m> and <m>h</m> because of tradition.
      What is important, is that you view <m>h</m> and <m>k</m>
      (as well as <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>)
      as constants:
      numbers that have some specific value and don't change in the context of one problem.
    </p>

    <p permid="Tys">
      Think about just one of these last equations: <m>y=k</m>.
      It says that the <m>y</m>-value is the same no matter where you are on the line.
      If you wanted to plot points on this line,
      you are free to move far to the left or far to the right on the <m>x</m>-axis,
      but then you always move up
      (or down)
      to make the <m>y</m>-value equal <m>k</m>.
      What does such a line look like?
    </p>

    <example permid="mOt">
      <p permid="byq">
        Let's plot the line with equation <m>y=3</m>.
        (Note that this is the same as <m>0x+1y=3</m>.)
      </p>

      <sidebyside permid="rym" widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

        <stack>
          <p permid="HFz">
            To plot some points, it doesn't matter what <m>x</m>-values we use.
            All that matters is that <m>y</m> is
            <em>always</em> <m>3</m>.
          </p>

          <p permid="nMI">
            A line like this is <term>horizontal</term>,
                <idx><h>horizontal line</h></idx>
            parallel to the horizontal axis.
            All lines with an equation in the form
            <me permid="IZn">
              y=k
            </me>
            (or, in standard form, <m>0x+By=C</m>) are <term>horizontal</term>.
          </p>
        </stack>

        <figure permid="TTR">
          <caption><m>y=3</m></caption>
          <image permid="Pyt">
            <description>a horizontal line at y=3</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(4,0) (5,0) (5,3)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0) (1,3)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-1,0) (-2,0) (-2,3)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-5,0) (-6,0) (-6,3)};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(5,3) (1,3) (-2,3) (-6,3)};
                    \addplot[primarycurve]{3};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <example permid="SVC">
      <p permid="Aba">
        Let's plot the line with equation <m>x=5</m>.
        (Note that this is the same as <m>1x+0y=5</m>.)
      </p>

      <sidebyside permid="XFv" widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

        <stack>
          <p permid="gij">
            The line has <m>x=5</m>, so to plot points,
            we are <em>required</em> to move over to <m>x=5</m>.
            From there, we have complete freedom to move however far we like up or down.
          </p>

          <p permid="Mps">
            A line like this is <term>vertical</term>,
                <idx><h>vertical line</h></idx>
            parallel to the vertical axis.
            All lines with an equation in the form
            <me permid="pgw">
              x=h
            </me>
            (or, in standard form, <m>Ax+0y=C</m>) are vertical.
          </p>
        </stack>

        <figure permid="swB">
          <caption><m>x=5</m></caption>
          <image permid="vFC">
            <description>a vertical line at x=5</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0) (5,5)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0) (5,1)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0) (5,-2)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (5,0) (5,-6)};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(5,5) (5,1) (5,-2) (5,-6)};
                    \addplot[primarycurve] coordinates {(5,-7) (5,7)};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <example permid="zcL">
      <title>Zero Slope</title>
      <p permid="YDK">
        In <xref ref="exercise-jogging-on-mt-hood">Checkpoint</xref>,
        we learned that a horizontal line's slope is
        <m>0\text{,}</m> because the distance doesn't change as time moves on.
        So the numerator in the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref> is <m>0</m>.
        Now, if we know a line's slope and its <m>y</m>-intercept,
        we can use <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="title">slope-intercept form</xref> to write its equation:
        <md permid="VnF">
          <mrow>y\amp=mx+b</mrow>
          <mrow>y\amp=0x+b</mrow>
          <mrow>y\amp=b</mrow>
        </md>
        This provides us with an alternative way to think about equations of horizontal lines.
        They have a certain <m>y</m>-intercept <m>b</m>,
        and they have slope <m>0</m>.
      </p>

      <p permid="EKT">
        We use horizontal lines to model scenarios where there is no change in <m>y</m>-values,
        like when Kato stopped for <m>12</m> hours (he deserved a rest)!
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise permid="gZh">
      <title>Plotting Points</title>
      <webwork>
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
                @x=(-2..2);
                @y=(-4.25)x5;
                $pts=MultiAnswer(map{($_%2==0)?$x[$_/2]:$y[($_-1)/2]}(0..9))->with(
                  singleResult => 1,
                  allowBlankAnswers => 1,
                  checker => sub {
                    my ($correct,$student,$self) = @_;
                    my @sx = @{$student}[0,2,4,6,8];
                    my @sy = @{$student}[1,3,5,7,9];
                    my $OK=1;
                    if ($sy[0]!=-4.25) {
                        $self->setMessage(1,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $self->setMessage(2,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $OK=0;
                      }
                    for my $i(1..4){
                      if ($sy[$i]!=-4.25) {
                        $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $OK=0;
                      }
                      for my $j(0..$i-1){
                        if ($sy[$i]==-4.25 and $sx[$i]==$sx[$j]) {
                          $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point was already used.");
                          $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point was already used.");
                          $OK=0;
                        }
                      }
                    }
                    return $OK;
                  }
                );
                $gr = init_graph(-7,-7,7,7,axes=>[0,0],grid=>[14,14],size=>[240,240]);
                $gr->lb('reset');
                for $j (-6..-1,1..6) {
                   $gr->lb( new Label($j,   0,  $j,'black','center','top'  ,'large'));
                   $gr->lb( new Label( 0,  $j,  $j,'black','right','middle','large'));
                };
                $gr->lb( new Label(7, 0, "x ",'black','right','bottom','large'));
                $gr->lb( new Label(0, 7, " y",'black','left','top','large'));
                for my $i(-2..2){$gr->stamps( closed_circle($i,-4.25,'blue') );}
                $gr->moveTo(0,-4.25);
                $gr->arrowTo(-7,-4.25,'blue',1);
                $gr->moveTo(0,-4.25);
                $gr->arrowTo(7,-4.25,'blue',1);
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p permid="ZnE">
              Suppose you need to plot the equation <m>y=-4.25</m>.
              Since the equation is in <q><m>y=</m></q> form,
              you decide to make a table of points.
              Fill out some points for this table.
            </p>

            <sidebyside permid="DME">

              <tabular permid="CeI">
                <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>

            </sidebyside>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="uHn">
            <p permid="tBU">
              We can use whatever values for <m>x</m> that we like,
              as long as they are all different.
              The equation tells us the <m>y</m>-value has to be <m>-4.25</m> each time.
            </p>

            <sidebyside permid="jTN">

              <tabular permid="RnG">
                <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>-4.25</m></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>

            </sidebyside>

            <p permid="ZJd">
              The reason we made a table was to help with plotting the line.
            </p>

            <sidebyside permid="QaW" widths="40%">
              <image permid="uAj" pg-name="$gr" />
            </sidebyside>
          </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <example permid="fjU">
      <title>Undefined Slope</title>
      <p permid="kSc">
        What is the slope of a vertical line?
        <xref ref="figure-vertical-lines">Figure</xref>
        shows three lines passing through the origin,
        each steeper than the last.
        In each graph, you can see a slope triangle that uses a
        <q>rise</q> of <m>4</m> each time.
      </p>

      <figure permid="dnD" xml:id="figure-vertical-lines">
        <caption />

        <sidebyside permid="wif" widths="31% 31% 31%">

          <image permid="bML">
            <description>a line with a slope of 4/4=1</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,
                            ymin=-1,]
                    \addplot+[] coordinates {(-1,-1) (7,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.5] {$\text{slope}=\frac{4}{4}=1$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (4,0)} node[above,pos=0.5] {$4$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(4,0) (4,4)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$4$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <image permid="HTU">
            <description>a line with a slope of 4/2=2, which is steeper than the first line</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,
                            ymin=-1,]
                    \addplot+[] coordinates {(-0.5,-1) (3.5,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.5] {$\text{slope}=\frac{4}{2}=2$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (2,0)} node[above,pos=0.5] {$2$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(2,0) (2,4)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$4$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <image permid="obd">
            <description>a linw with a slope of 4/1=4, which is steeper than the previous two lines</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,
                            ymin=-1,]
                    \addplot+[] coordinates {(-0.25,-1) (1.75,7)} node[above,sloped,pos=0.75] {$\text{slope}=\frac{4}{1}=4$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (1,0)} node[above,pos=0.5] {$1$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(1,0) (1,4)} node[right,pos=0.5] {$4$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </sidebyside>

      </figure>

      <p permid="QZl">
        If we continued making the line steeper and steeper until it was vertical,
        the slope triangle would still have a
        <q>rise</q> of <m>4</m>,
        but the <q>run</q> would become smaller and smaller, closer to <m>0</m>.
        And then the slope would be <m>m=\frac{4}{\text{very small}}=\text{very large}</m>.
        So the slope of a vertical line can be thought of as
        <q>infinitely large.</q>
      </p>

      <p permid="xgu">
        If we actually try to compute the slope using the slope triangle when the run is <m>0</m>,
        we would have <m>\frac{4}{0}</m>, which is undefined.
        So we also say that the slope of a vertical line is <em>undefined</em>.
        Some people say that a vertical line <em>has no slope.</em>
      </p>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p permid="zFB">
        Be careful not to mix up <q>no slope</q>
        (which means <q>its slope is undefined</q>)
        with <q>has slope <m>0</m>.</q>
        If a line has slope <m>0</m>,
        it <em>does</em> have a slope.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <exercise permid="Ngq">
      <title>Plotting Points</title>
      <webwork>
          <setup>

            <pg-code>
                @x=(3.14)x5;
                @y=(-2..2);
                $pts=MultiAnswer(map{($_%2==0)?$x[$_/2]:$y[($_-1)/2]}(0..9))->with(
                  singleResult => 1,
                  allowBlankAnswers => 1,
                  checker => sub {
                    my ($correct,$student,$self) = @_;
                    my @sx = @{$student}[0,2,4,6,8];
                    my @sy = @{$student}[1,3,5,7,9];
                    my $OK=1;
                    if ($sx[0]!=3.14) {
                        $self->setMessage(1,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $self->setMessage(2,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $OK=0;
                      }
                    for my $i(1..4){
                      if ($sx[$i]!=3.14) {
                        $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point is not on the line.");
                        $OK=0;
                      }
                      for my $j(0..$i-1){
                        if ($sx[$i]==3.14 and $sy[$i]==$sy[$j]) {
                          $self->setMessage(2*$i+1,"This point was already used.");
                          $self->setMessage(2*$i+2,"This point was already used.");
                          $OK=0;
                        }
                      }
                    }
                    return $OK;
                  }
                );
                $gr = init_graph(-7,-7,7,7,axes=>[0,0],grid=>[14,14],size=>[240,240]);
                $gr->lb('reset');
                for $j (-6..-1,1..6) {
                   $gr->lb( new Label($j,   0,  $j,'black','center','top'  ,'large'));
                   $gr->lb( new Label( 0,  $j,  $j,'black','right','middle','large'));
                };
                $gr->lb( new Label(7, 0, "x ",'black','right','bottom','large'));
                $gr->lb( new Label(0, 7, " y",'black','left','top','large'));
                for my $i(-2..2){$gr->stamps( closed_circle(3.14,$i,'blue') );}
                $gr->moveTo(3.14,0);
                $gr->arrowTo(3.14,7,'blue',1);
                $gr->moveTo(3.14,0);
                $gr->arrowTo(3.14,-7,'blue',1);
            </pg-code>
          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p permid="FuN">
              Suppose you need to plot the equation <m>x=3.14</m>.
              You decide to try making a table of points.
              Fill out some points for this table.
            </p>

            <sidebyside permid="cpo">

              <tabular permid="ilR">
                <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                  <cell><var name="$pts" width="10" /></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>

            </sidebyside>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="aOw">
            <p permid="FQm">
              Since the equation says <m>x</m> is always the number <m>3.14</m>,
              we have to use this for the <m>x</m> value in all the points.
              This is different from how we would plot a
              <q><m>y=</m></q> equation,
              where we would use several different <m>x</m>-values.
              We can use whatever values for <m>y</m> that we like,
              as long as they are all different.
            </p>

            <sidebyside permid="Iwx">

              <tabular permid="xuP">
                <row bottom="medium" halign="center">
                  <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>3.14</m></cell>
