        Let <m>x</m> represent the price of a new <m>60</m>-inch television at Target on Black Friday
        (which was <m>\$650</m>),
        and let <m>y</m> be the number of hours you will watch something on this TV over its lifetime.
        What is the relationship between <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>?
      </p>

      <sidebyside permid="UKP" widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <p permid="pBV">
          Well, there is no getting around the fact that <m>x=650</m>.
          As for <m>y</m>,
          without any extra information about your viewing habits,
          it could theoretically be as low as <m>0</m> or it could be anything larger than that.
          If we graph this scenario,
          we have to graph the equation <m>x=650</m> which we now know to give a vertical line,
          and we get <xref ref="figure-television">Figure</xref>.
        </p>

        <figure permid="VJe" xml:id="figure-television">
          <caption>New TV: hours watched versus purchase price; negative <m>y</m>-values omitted since they make no sense in context</caption>
          <image permid="Uim">
